The Goal

Our goal is compare FIFA19 game statistics to the real 18/19 match statistics. FIFA19’s statistics are based on the 17/18 real season, so we are going to test how well FIFA19 can predict the outcome of the season following its release (18/19 season).

Motivation

As a group, we wanted to do a project that would directly address one of society’s biggest questions… “Are video games actually good for something”? There is a lot of controversy over the topic because one side believes that video games “rot the brain” and yield no significant benefit to the player, while the other side believes that video games can be an outlet for creativity and imagination. Our group personally believes that video games are a must in this world (being biased of course since we were born and raised with them and still continue to play them), however, our personal beliefs may not be enough to convince someone else that video games are essential to society. We don’t plan on making a radical video game hater into a video game devotee, but we do plan on chipping away at the argument, even if it is only about one aspect.

The approach we decided to take was with sports, a common ground between some people who hate the idea of video games, and who love sports. We want to predict the best soccer team in the European League next season. You might be asking how this is possible, but, with the power of Machine Learning and Data Analysis, the sky’s the limit. We are going to be utilizing the player ratings from the famous EA soccer game, FIFA. The data will be collected from the 2017, 2018, and the 2019 seasons in order to create a model to accurately predict winning percentage. Our thinking is that the team with the highest winning percentage from the model will be the “best team” in the league. With this knowledge you could wow your friends with your extensive knowledge on the sport, and you could call out who would win a game more accurately.

The project below will show you how to do this step by step, all links for important vernacular in the soccer industry are listed below, along with resources to help you understand things that are going on in the code that aren’t so obvious. I hope you’re ready to impress your friends, because this will be a game changer.

Entity Resolution Function

  • The names of each club that are listed on the real season datasets and within the FIFA dataset sometimes slightly differ in name. This is because many of the club names in the real season dataset are in Latin1 encoding rather than UTF-8 encoding, and therefore perceived as inequal.
    • In order to successfully match these clubs, there is a need for some entity resolution.
  • Entity Resolution:
    • The matching of entities based on a similarity threshold. Sometimes entities will have slightly different names or values on two different datasets even though they are referring to the same entity. Entity resolution allows for these entities to be matched even if they are not perfectly identical.
  • This particular entity resolution uses the adist() function as part of the RecordLinkage package. This function finds the distance between two character vectors.
  • This distance is called the Levenshtein distance.
    • More can be found about this function HERE
  • In some cases the adist() function still does not work. In order to manually change the encoding the iconv() function can be used.
    • More info on iconv() function can be found HERE
library(RecordLinkage)

club_similarity <- function(c1, c2){
  club1 <- as.character(c1)
  club1_encode <- iconv(club1, from="latin1", to="UTF-8")
  club2 <- as.character(c2)
  
  if(is.na(adist(club1, club2)[[1]])){
    if(club1_encode == club2){
      similarity <- TRUE
    } else{
      similarity <- FALSE
    } 
  } else if (adist(club1, club2)[[1]] == 1){
    similarity <- TRUE
  } else{
    similarity <- FALSE
  }
  return(similarity)
}

Data Management and Data Cleaning

  1. Combine all of the previously created csv files to have a full 18/19 season containing the 5 leagues.
  2. Go through matches and count the number of wins and total number of games played by each club.
  3. Each league has their own specific number of games played per season. Count the number of games played by each club.
    • More information about games per season can be found HERE and HERE
  4. Divide the number of games won by the total number of games played in a season and multiply by 100 to find the season win percentage.
  5. Go through FIFA dataframe to find the average rating of each club by taking the mean of the overall rating of each player for each club.
    • Information on how FIFA obtains their ratings can be found HERE
  6. Make a new dataframe containg only the clubs and their corresponding team rating.
  7. Combine the real season win percentages with the team ratings from FIFA using a left join on the seasonal data.
  8. Perform entity resolution on any of the entities that did not match properly in the left join
    • Join is performed before entity resolution to improve efficiency. This prevents the need to perform entity resolution on entities that successfully matched
  9. Recombine the dataframes using the left join with updated club names
  10. Create a new dataframe containing each players individual ratings, their clubs winning percentage, the players wage, adn the players age.
#Step (1)
#This can only be done since all of the columns of each of the consituent dataframes have the same columns
#Rename the division titles by their league

SZN_df <- rbind(ENG_df, FRA_df, GER_df, ITA_df, SPA_df) %>%
  rename(Club = Winner)
SZN_df$Div <- gsub("E0", "Premier League", SZN_df$Div)
SZN_df$Div <- gsub("D1", "Bundesliga", SZN_df$Div)
SZN_df$Div <- gsub("F1", "Ligue 1", SZN_df$Div)
SZN_df$Div <- gsub("I1", "Serie A", SZN_df$Div)
SZN_df$Div <- gsub("SP1", "La Liga", SZN_df$Div)

#Step (2)
#Count function gives a count of each unique value in the inputted column.

win_perc <- count(SZN_df, SZN_df$Club) %>%
  rename(Club="SZN_df$Club")

home <- count(SZN_df, SZN_df$HomeTeam)
away <- count(SZN_df, SZN_df$AwayTeam)

#Step (3)
#Convert count column from factor to numeric. 
#Since each club plays either 17 or 19 games the column is formatted as a factor, which cannot be added together. 
#Statement says that if the current value of the column is the factor level "17" then replace the value with the numeric 17, otherwise replace the value with numeric 19.

home$n <- ifelse(home$n %in% c("17"), 17, 19)
away$n <- ifelse(away$n %in% c("17"), 17, 19)

#Step (4)
#Add column of the summed away and home games played to find the total games played by each team. 
#Convert the columns into matrices before adding. 
#Convert the numbers to doubles when dividing to avoid truncating the value. 
#Then multiply by 100 to give total season win percentge for each club.

win_perc <- win_perc %>% 
  mutate(games_played = (as.matrix(home$n) + as.matrix(away$n))) %>%
  mutate(perc = as.double(n/games_played) * 100) %>%
  left_join(SZN_df, by="Club") %>% 
  select(Div, Club, perc) %>%
  unique()

#Step (7)

team_combined <- win_perc %>% 
  left_join(FIFA_rating, by="Club") %>%
  select(Div, Club, perc, team_rating) %>%
  unique()

#Step (8)
#Check for any rows with missing values and perform entity resolution to update club name with corresponding entity within the FIFA dataset.

missing_entities <- !complete.cases(team_combined)
for(row in 1:nrow(team_combined)){
  if(missing_entities[row] == TRUE){
    for(f_row in 1:nrow(FIFA_rating)){
      if (club_similarity(team_combined[row, 1], FIFA_rating[f_row, 1])){
        team_combined[row, "Club"] = FIFA_rating[f_row, "Club"]
      }
    }
  }
}

#Step (9)
#Get rid of any rows that were still not sucessfully linked within the entity resolution

team_combined <- team_combined %>%
  left_join(FIFA_rating, by = "Club") %>%
  rename(team_rating = team_rating.y) %>%
  select(Div, Club, perc, team_rating)
team_combined <- team_combined[complete.cases(team_combined),]

Exploratory Data Analysis

During exploratory data analysis we begin to visualize our previously cleaned data to see if there are any interesting correlations that we can draw.

Let’s make one plot for each of the 5 leagues we are looking at.

  • Each plot has the corresponding club teams on the x axis and the club’s corresponding player ratings on the y axis.
  • The plots use a violin distribution to see the distribution of the team’s player ratings
library(ggplot2)

#Club team names on the x axis are shortened and angled to improve readability of the plots
for(var in unique(player_combined$Div)){
  print(ggplot(player_combined[player_combined$Div == var,],
               aes(x=factor(Club), y=Rating), color=club) + 
                  geom_violin() + 
                  scale_x_discrete(label=function(x) stringr::str_trunc(x, 8)) +
                  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle=90)) +
                  labs(title=paste("League: ", var), x="Clubs", y="Player Rating"))
}

We can also make a plot to see the overall player rating distribution for each league

  • This plot uses a polygon distribution to represent the count of each rating
  • The red line represents the median player rating for the league
  • The blue lines represent (Median +- (1.5 * Inner Quartile Range)), or the threshold for outlying player ratings. Player ratings above or below the blue lines represent players that have extremely high or low player ratings related to their league.
#A plot is created for each of the 5 leagues, using vline to plot 3 lines representing lower outlier, median and higher outlier
for(var in unique(player_combined$Div)){
  median <- median(player_combined[player_combined$Div==var,]$Rating)
  iqr <- IQR(player_combined[player_combined$Div==var,]$Rating)
  rating_count <- count(player_combined[player_combined$Div==var,], Rating)
  
  print(rating_count %>% ggplot(aes(x=Rating, y=n)) +
                        geom_polygon() +
                        geom_vline(aes(xintercept=median), color="red", size=2) +
                        geom_vline(aes(xintercept = median+(1.5*iqr)), color = "blue") +
                        geom_vline(aes(xintercept = median-(1.5*iqr)), color = "blue") +
                        labs(title=paste("League: ", var), x="Player Ratings", y="Count"))
}

Finally, we can create a density plot to show all of the league’s player ratings side by side. This plot gives us a good idea of how FIFA ratings are distributed across different leagues

counting <- count(player_combined, Rating)
factor <- factor(player_combined$Div)

player_combined %>% ggplot(aes(x=Rating, group=Div, fill=Div)) +
  geom_density(adjust=0.8, alpha=0.6) +
  labs(title="Density of Player Ratings by League", x="Player Rating", y="Density")

From these plots we can see that FIFA uses a similar distribution for it’s player ratings across leagues

  • The majority of players have ratings within 70-80.
  • There is a second smaller peak of player ratings around the 60’s
  • All other players fall somewhere in between with some variety.

Hypothesis Testing

Now that we have some idea of what our data looks like, let’s see if we can draw any relevant correlations.

We’ll start by seeing if there is any correlation between a player’s age and their player rating within FIFA.

library(broom)

player_combined %>% ggplot(aes(x=Age, y=Rating)) + 
  geom_point() + 
  geom_smooth(method=lm) +
  labs(title="Player Rating vs. Age Across All Leagues", x="Age(Years)", y="Player Rating")

tidy(lm(Rating~Age, player_combined))
## # A tibble: 2 x 5
##   term        estimate std.error statistic   p.value
##   <chr>          <dbl>     <dbl>     <dbl>     <dbl>
## 1 (Intercept)   52.7      0.635       82.9 0.       
## 2 Age            0.809    0.0252      32.1 8.73e-194

As we can see from the fitted linear model, There is a very clear correlation between player rating and player age. We know this because the p-value for the estimated rating coefficient is 8.727e-194, which is nearly 0. A p-value below .01 would be enough to prove that there is a statistically significant relationship between player rating and age. However, we can also see that a linear model is perhaps not the best model for this data. It seems parabolic rather than linear.

Next, we can test whether there is any correlation between player’s wages their rating.

From both of these plots we can determine that there is also a clear correlation between player rating and wage. The p-value is 0 meaning that the estimate for the slope is statistically significant from 0 (or no correlation).

Machine Learning

Next, we will be creating a random forest model in order to see how well the winning percentages can be predicted based solely on the team ratings on FIFA. In order to perform this we need to randomly select 20 club/teams from our clean data. We will use these 20 clubs to train our random forest of 500 trees.

library(randomForest)
library(pracma)
set.seed(654321)

#Create a new dataframe without Division and Club names
#Augument a column to represent row indices to help with sampling

ml_df <- team_combined %>% 
  mutate(row_index = 0) %>%
  select(row_index, team_rating, perc)
for(row in 1:nrow(ml_df)){
  ml_df[row, "row_index"] = row
}

#Create the training set by taking 20 random rows

training_set <- ml_df[sample(nrow(ml_df), 20),]
sampled_indices <- as.vector(training_set$row_index)
training_set <- training_set %>%
  select(team_rating, perc)

#Create testing set by taking all rows not used in the training set.

testing_set <- ml_df[-sampled_indices,] %>%
  select(team_rating, perc)

#Train the random forest model using the training set data with 500 trees.

rf <- randomForest(
  perc~.,
  ntree=500,
  data=training_set
)

Now we must use our model to predict winning percentages based on our testing set of team ratings. After we obtain our predictions, we can compare them to our real season winning percentages to identify how accurate our model is.

  1. Create the output dataframe that contains the testing team ratings, win percentages, predicted win percentages, and the difference between the prediction and the actual value.
    • Also create a long dataframe that relates team rating to win percentage conditioned on whether its an actual value or a prediction. This will be helpful for plotting the data.
#Create one column for the predicted win percentage and one column for the difference between the predicted and real win percentage

output <- testing_set %>%
  mutate(prediction = predict(rf, newdata=testing_set)) %>%
  mutate(difference = (prediction - perc))

#Creating a 3 column dataframe for just actual data

actual <- testing_set %>%
  mutate(datatype = "Actual") %>%
  select(datatype, team_rating, perc)

#Creating a 3 column dataframe for just prediction data

predicted <- testing_set %>%
  mutate(perc = predict(rf, newdata=testing_set)) %>%
  mutate(datatype = "Predicted") %>%
  select(datatype, team_rating, perc)

#Binding both the predicted and actual dataframes to be used for graphing

graphing <- rbind(actual, predicted)

  1. Next lets look at a plot of predicted win percentage vs. actual win percentage
output %>% ggplot(aes(x=perc, y=prediction)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth(method=lm) +
  labs(title="Predicted Win Percentage vs. Actual Win Percentage", 
       x="Actual Win Percentage", 
       y="Predicted Win Percentage"
  )

tidy(lm(prediction~perc, output))
## # A tibble: 2 x 5
##   term        estimate std.error statistic  p.value
##   <chr>          <dbl>     <dbl>     <dbl>    <dbl>
## 1 (Intercept)   32.1      2.69       11.9  6.40e-18
## 2 perc           0.364    0.0520      7.01 1.78e- 9

It is important to note that if the predictions were 100% accurate the predicted and actual values would be identical. A 100% accurate predictive model would result in the slope of this graph being exactly 1. If the slope of the line was 1 this would mean that for every increase in actual win percentage there would be a mirrored increase in the predicted value.

However, we can see from the linear model that the slope is instead 0.3645. This means that the value of the predicted win percentage increases by 0.3645 percent for every 1 percent increase of actual win percentage. This means that the predictive model was not perfectly accurate.

It is also important to note, however, that the p-value for this slope coefficient estimate is 1.784e-9. So, while we did not get a perfect slope of 1, there is still a statistically significant direct correlation between actual and predicted value.

  1. The last plot we can look at is a plot of differences between predicted and actual win percentages vs. team rating.
output %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x=team_rating, y=difference)) +
    geom_point() +
    geom_smooth(method=lm) +
    labs(
      title="Difference in Predicted and Actual Win Percentages vs. Team Rating",
      x="Team Rating",
      y="Difference in Predicted and Actual Win Percentages"
    )

A difference of 0 means that the predictive model was accurate. From this plot we can see that the predictive model is most accurate at a team rating of about 73. We can also see that it typically overestimates at lower team ratings and underestimates at higher team ratings.

  1. The last step of analysis is performing a two-tailed t test for difference of means. The null hypothesis of this test is that there is no difference between the predicted and actual win percentages. The alternative hypothesis is that there is a difference between the predicted and actual win percentages. In order to prove that this predictive model works, we need to fail to reject the null hypothesis, because we do not want the two values to be statistically different from each other.
t.test(output$perc, output$prediction)
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  output$perc and output$prediction
## t = -0.39628, df = 101.36, p-value = 0.6927
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -5.562505  3.710072
## sample estimates:
## mean of x mean of y 
##  49.02195  49.94817

From out two-tailed t-test we have obtained a p-value of 0.6927. This p-value is much too large to reject the null hypothesis. This means that since that we failed to reject the null hypothesis, the predicted win percentage and actual win percentage are not statistically different from one another.

Conclusion

Video games and even following sports can sometimes be seen as a waste of time, but there is a lot of analytics and science that goes into them. Electronic Arts takes the time very year to evaluate player performance to finalize their ratings for the next FIFA game. The ratings are based on some true performances in the past, and can sometimes be a good indication towards how a team will perform in real life. A lot of people invest money and place bets on sports as a source of income, and it would be interesting if a team’s rating would dirrectly correlate to the winning percentage and help the betters out. Our model did have some success, but wasn’t always completely accurate. This could be due to the fact that we created a model with random teams from each league. If we handpicked some teams with high ratings, some with low ratings, and some with average ratings we might have had a more accurate model. This was interesting however, because we did find a positive correlation between a teams FIFA rating and their winning percentage, with a p-value of 4.644e-13. The slope of our actual vs predicted line was 0.3645, and if our model as perfect it should have been 1. The p-value was 1.784e-9, so even though are model wasn’t perfect we can declare that there is definitely some sort of positive correlation between a team’s FIFA rating and their real life winning percentage. Although overall FIFA rating takes into account a lot of players and skills, in the future it would be best to account for attacking rating, defending rating and maybe some other numbers to predict how each team would do against another based on the attacking, defending, and other soccer/football skills they possess. Sports science/mathematics is a very difficult topic because there are many upsets that can occur in the sports world based on a multitude of factors, like Leicester City in the 2015/2016 Premier League season. They won the Premier league after coming in 14th place out of 20 teams the previous year, and the year before that they were playing in the English Championship, which is like the second division or minor league. It isn’t always wise to trust the team with the better players or higher FIFA ratings to always do well. Our model got the general trend correct, in which a higher rated team would have a better winning percentage, but wasn’t able to predict the winning percentage exactly.
